From: Stephen Wheet <stephen@wheetazlab.io>
Date: Sat, 7 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] net: macb: Flush TSTART write to RP1 over PCIe

The RP1 southbridge on Raspberry Pi CM5 / Pi 5 exposes the Cadence GEM
(macb) ethernet controller behind a PCIe link.  PCIe uses "posted writes"
for MMIO: the CPU fires the write and moves on without waiting for the
device to actually process it.  Under load, the write of NCR |= TSTART
can be silently dropped or arrive after the hardware has already checked
whether to queue a new transmission, leaving the TX ring permanently
stalled with no error interrupt, rising PHY link state, or watchdog
timeout visible to the kernel.

Fix by following every TSTART write with a non-posted NCR readback.
A PCIe non-posted read creates an implicit ordering barrier: the bus
fabric cannot return the read response until all prior posted writes from
the same requester have been delivered.  After the read returns, TSTART
is guaranteed to have reached RP1.

The readback is added in both:
  - macb_start_xmit()    -- the primary per-packet TX start path
  - macb_tx_restart()    -- the NAPI-driven TX retry path

Observed symptom on DeskPi Super6C (CM5, Talos Linux 1.12.x / kernel
6.18.x): nodes become unreachable after minutes-to-hours of uptime with
no kernel errors.  Recovery: `ip link set end0 down && ip link set end0
up`.  Stable on Talos 1.11.x / kernel 6.12.x (RP1 supported via
siderolabs/pkgs downstream patches, now mainline since 6.13).

Based on Raspberry Pi downstream fix for rpi-6.12.y:
  https://github.com/raspberrypi/linux/commit/359f37f0faefb712add32a39f98751aea67d5c1f

The RPi fix used a queue->tx_pending flag that has a different meaning
in mainline 6.18 (it is the ethtool ring buffer size).  This version
instead uses the standard PCIe read-after-write barrier idiom, which
is both simpler and covers the macb_tx_restart() path as well.

Upstream candidate: mainline commit bf9cf80 ("net: macb: Fix tx/rx
malfunction after phy link down and up") addresses a related ring-
pointer mismatch but has not yet been backported to the 6.18.x stable
series as of 6.18.15.  This patch addresses the MMIO write ordering
root cause independently.

Link: https://github.com/siderolabs/sbc-raspberrypi/issues/82
Signed-off-by: Stephen Wheet <stephen@wheetazlab.io>
---
 drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c | 8 ++++++++
 1 file changed, 8 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/cadence/macb_main.c
@@ -1716,6 +1716,10 @@ static void macb_tx_restart(struct macb_queue *queue)
 
 	spin_lock(&bp->lock);
 	macb_writel(bp, NCR, macb_readl(bp, NCR) | MACB_BIT(TSTART));
+	/* RP1 is behind PCIe; posted TSTART writes can be silently dropped.
+	 * A non-posted read forces all prior posted writes to be delivered
+	 * before we return, guaranteeing TSTART reached the hardware. */
+	(void)macb_readl(bp, NCR);
 	spin_unlock(&bp->lock);
 
 out_tx_ptr_unlock:
@@ -2390,6 +2394,10 @@ static netdev_tx_t macb_start_xmit(struct sk_buff *skb, struct net_device *dev)
 	spin_lock(&bp->lock);
 	macb_writel(bp, NCR, macb_readl(bp, NCR) | MACB_BIT(TSTART));
+	/* RP1 is behind PCIe; posted TSTART writes can be silently dropped.
+	 * A non-posted read forces all prior posted writes to be delivered
+	 * before we return, guaranteeing TSTART reached the hardware. */
+	(void)macb_readl(bp, NCR);
 	spin_unlock(&bp->lock);
 
 	if (CIRC_SPACE(queue->tx_head, queue->tx_tail, bp->tx_ring_size) < 1)
